20","Abt 1225":"about 1225","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1260":"1260","1180":"1180","Abt 1260":"about 1260","1225":"1225","1244":"1244","1298":"1298","after 1240":"after 1240","after 1244":"after 1244","Linlithgowshire, Scotland":"West Lothian, Scotland, United Kingdom","Dundaff, Stirling, Scotland":"Stirlingshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Noble","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and French: status name or nickname from Middle English, Old French <i>noble</i> ‘high-born, distinguished, illustrious’ (from Latin <i>nobilis</i>), denoting someone of lofty birth or character, or someone who poses as a nobleman, or perhaps also ironically someone of low station. The surname has been established in Ireland since the 13th century, but was re-introduced in the 17th century and is now found mainly in Ulster. Compare French   Lenoble  .","Americanized form of Jewish (Ashkenazic) and German <b>Knöbel</b>,   Knobel  , and   Nobel  .","Spanish: nickname from <i>noble</i> ‘noble’ or ‘courteous, kind’ (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Lenoble","meanings":["French: variant, with fused masculine definite article <i>le</i>, of   Noble   ‘high-born, distinguished, illustrious’."]},{"name":"Nobile","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Rocco, Angelo, Agostino, Antonio, Carmine, Ciro, Gaetano, Giovani, Giovanni, Lucio, Onofrio.","Italian: nickname from <i>nobile</i> ‘noble’ (see   Noble  )."]},{"name":"Nobles","meanings":["English: variant of   Noble  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Noblett","meanings":["English (Lancashire) and Irish (of French Huguenot origin): from a diminutive of <i>noble</i> (see   Noble  ).","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Nobelot</i>, a double diminutive of <b>Nobb</b> (see   Nobbe  )."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Noble was born about 1225, in West Lothian, Scotland, United Kingdom as the daughter of Unknown. She had at least 1 son with David Graham. She died about 1260, at the age of 37."},"et":{"Abt 1225–Abt 1260":"umbes 1225–umbes 1260","1225–1260":"1225–1260","1220–1272":"1220–1272","1180–1272":"1180–1272","1240–1297":"1240–1297","1244–1298":"1244–1298","–Male":"Surnud","1297":"1297","1220":"1220","Abt 1225":"umbes 1225","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1260":"1260","1180":"1180","Abt 1260":"umbes 1260","1225":"1225","1244":"1244","1298":"1298","after 1240":"pärast 1240","after 1244":"pärast 1244","Linlithgowshire, Scotland":"West Lothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Dundaff, Stirling, Scotland":"Stirlingshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"Abt 1225–Abt 1260":"noin 1225–noin 1260","1225–1260":"1225–1260","1220–1272":"1220–1272","1180–1272":"1180–1272","1240–1297":"1240–1297","1244–1298":"1244–1298","–Male":"Kuollut","1297":"1297","1220":"1220","Abt 1225":"noin 1225","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1260":"1260","1180":"1180","Abt 1260":"noin 1260","1225":"1225","1244":"1244","1298":"1298","after 1240":"1240 jälkeen","after 1244":"1244 jälkeen","Linlithgowshire, Scotland":"West Lo